Explanation:

- The provided controller (app/Http/Controllers/Admin/CommentController.php) implements destroy(Comment $comment) which:
  - Calls $comment->delete();
  - Returns redirect()->route('admin.comments.index')->withSuccess(__('comments.deleted'));
- The route registration in routes/admin.php uses Route::resource('comments', CommentController::class)->only(..., 'destroy'), so the controller destroy action is bound to a DELETE request on the resource route (in practice DELETE /admin/comments/{comment} under the admin route group).
- The controller returns a RedirectResponse on success (Laravel's redirect()->route(...) produces a 302 Found redirect by default and sets a flash session value).
- Possible runtime outcomes to reflect in responses:
  - 302 Found: successful deletion â€” redirect to the comments index. The Location header carries the redirect URL.
  - 401 Unauthorized / unauthenticated: guest access (middleware may redirect to login; for APIs it could be 401).
  - 403 Forbidden: authenticated user lacks permission to delete the comment.
  - 404 Not Found: route-model binding fails because the Comment does not exist.
  - 419 Page Expired: CSRF token mismatch on form submission (web routes).
  - 500 Internal Server Error: unexpected server error.
- The Response Objects below follow Swagger 2.0 Response Object shape: keys are status codes and each has a description; for the 302 redirect a Location header is declared (inline, not using $ref).

